  <!-- Activity MET table -->
  <div class="article-section">
    <h2>Calories Burned by Activity — Quick Reference</h2>
    <p>The table below shows approximate calories burned per 30 minutes for a 70 kg adult. Your result scales proportionally with your weight.</p>
    <div class="card" style="padding:0;overflow:hidden;margin:16px 0;">
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th>Activity</th><th>30 min (70 kg)</th><th>30 min (85 kg)</th><th>Intensity</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Walking (5 km/h)</td><td>~122 kcal</td><td>~148 kcal</td><td>Low</td></tr>
          <tr class="highlight-row"><td>Running (10 km/h)</td><td>~343 kcal</td><td>~417 kcal</td><td>High</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Cycling (moderate)</td><td>~238 kcal</td><td>~289 kcal</td><td>Moderate</td></tr>
          <tr class="highlight-row"><td>Swimming (freestyle)</td><td>~245 kcal</td><td>~298 kcal</td><td>Moderate–High</td></tr>
          <tr><td>HIIT</td><td>~280 kcal</td><td>~340 kcal</td><td>Very High</td></tr>
          <tr class="highlight-row"><td>Weight training</td><td>~175 kcal</td><td>~213 kcal</td><td>Moderate</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Yoga (hatha)</td><td>~140 kcal</td><td>~170 kcal</td><td>Low</td></tr>
          <tr class="highlight-row"><td>Jump rope</td><td>~350 kcal</td><td>~425 kcal</td><td>Very High</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Hiking (moderate)</td><td>~140 kcal</td><td>~170 kcal</td><td>Moderate</td></tr>
          <tr class="highlight-row"><td>Housework (general)</td><td>~122 kcal</td><td>~148 kcal</td><td>Low</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h2>How Many Calories Does Walking Burn?</h2>
    <p>Walking is consistently underrated as a calorie-burning activity because the per-minute burn is low — but the cumulative effect of daily walking is substantial. A 70 kg person walking at 5 km/h burns approximately <strong>245 calories per hour</strong> (4 calories per minute). Key factors:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Body weight:</strong> A 90 kg person burns about 30% more calories per step than a 70 kg person</li>
      <li><strong>Speed:</strong> Walking at 6.5 km/h (brisk) burns ~35% more than 5 km/h (moderate)</li>
      <li><strong>Incline:</strong> Walking uphill at 5% grade increases calorie burn by approximately 50%</li>
      <li><strong>10,000 steps:</strong> Burns approximately 300–500 calories for most adults, depending on weight and pace</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="callout"><p>💡 For most people, daily walking is the most sustainable form of calorie-burning exercise. A 30-minute daily walk adds up to ~850 kcal burned per week — equivalent to losing about 0.1 kg of fat per week from exercise alone.</p></div>

    <h2>How Many Calories Does Running Burn?</h2>
    <p>Running burns approximately <strong>8–12 calories per minute</strong> for most adults — making it one of the highest-calorie activities available. A 70 kg person running at 10 km/h for 30 minutes burns approximately 340 calories. Key points:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Running pace matters less than you think — slower running burns almost as many calories per km as faster running (you just cover the distance more slowly)</li>
      <li>A 5 km run burns approximately 300–400 calories regardless of pace for most adults</li>
      <li>Running outdoors burns slightly more calories than treadmill running (terrain variation, wind resistance)</li>
      <li>Post-exercise calorie burn (EPOC) from running adds approximately 5–10% to total burn</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>How This Calculator Works</h2>
    <p>This calculator uses <strong>MET values</strong> (Metabolic Equivalent of Task) — a standardised measure of how much energy an activity requires relative to rest. The formula is:</p>
    <div class="card" style="padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;font-family:monospace;font-size:.9rem;text-align:center;">
      Calories = MET × body weight (kg) × duration (hours)
    </div>
    <p>MET values are sourced from the <em>Compendium of Physical Activities</em> (Ainsworth et al., 2011), the standard reference used by exercise physiologists. These are population-average estimates; individual variation of ±10–20% is normal depending on fitness level, efficiency, and terrain.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How are calories burned calculated?</button>
      <div class="faq-a">Calories burned are calculated using MET values (Metabolic Equivalent of Task). The formula is: Calories = MET × weight in kg × duration in hours. MET values represent how many times more energy an activity requires compared to rest. Walking has a MET of about 3.5, running 8–11, cycling 6–9.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How many calories do you burn walking 10,000 steps?</button>
      <div class="faq-a">Walking 10,000 steps burns approximately 300–500 calories for most adults, depending on body weight and walking pace. A 70 kg person walking at moderate pace (5 km/h) for approximately 80–90 minutes burns around 350 calories. Heavier people burn more calories per step due to the higher energy cost of moving greater mass.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Does exercise burn enough calories to lose weight?</button>
      <div class="faq-a">Exercise contributes to weight loss but is rarely sufficient alone. A 30-minute run burns 250–400 calories, which can be undone by a single snack. The most effective approach combines moderate calorie restriction with exercise. Exercise also improves metabolic health, preserves muscle during weight loss, and improves long-term weight maintenance.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Which exercise burns the most calories?</button>
      <div class="faq-a">High-intensity activities burn the most calories per minute: running (8–12 kcal/min), rowing (8–10 kcal/min), cycling fast (8–10 kcal/min), jumping rope (10–12 kcal/min), and swimming (6–8 kcal/min). However, sustainability matters more than per-minute burn. A 60-minute walk burns more total calories than a 10-minute sprint most people cannot sustain.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Are calories burned estimates accurate?</button>
      <div class="faq-a">MET-based calculations are estimates with typical accuracy of ±10–20%. Individual variation in fitness level, efficiency, and terrain significantly affects actual burn. Fitness trackers and smartwatches add heart rate data but are still estimates. Use these numbers as a guide, not a precise measurement.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div style="background:#F0F7F4;border:1px solid #B7DDD0;border-radius:12px;padding:20px 24px;font-size:0.82rem;color:#2D4A3E;line-height:1.8;margin:24px 0;">
    <strong style="display:block;margin-bottom:8px;">📚 References</strong>
    <ol style="margin:8px 0 8px 18px;padding:0;">
      <li>Ainsworth BE et al. (2011). <em>2011 Compendium of Physical Activities</em>. Med Sci Sports Exerc. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1249/MSS.0b013e31821ece12" style="color:var(--accent);">doi:10.1249/MSS.0b013e31821ece12</a></li>
      <li>Mifflin MD et al. (1990). <em>A new predictive equation for resting energy expenditure</em>. Am J Clin Nutr. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1093/ajcn/51.2.241" style="color:var(--accent);">doi:10.1093/ajcn/51.2.241</a></li>
    </ol>
    Estimates only. Not a substitute for professional advice. Last updated June 2026.
  </div>

  <div class="related">
